Equilateral triangle $ABC$ and square $BCDE$ are coplanar, as shown. What is the number of degrees in the measure of angle $CAD$?

[asy]
size(70);
draw((0,0)--(20,0)--(20,20)--(0,20)--cycle);
draw((0,20)--(10,37.3)--(20,20));
draw((10,37.3)--(20,0));
label("$A$",(10,37.3),N);
label("$B$",(0,20),W);
label("$C$",(20,20),E);
label("$D$",(20,0),E);
label("$E$",(0,0),W);
[/asy] ||| To find angle CAD, we note that triangle ABC is equilateral, so \angle ABC = 60^\circ. The angles around point C total 360 degrees, and we also have a right angle at D, thus \angle BCD = 90^\circ. So, we have \angle ACD = \angle ABC + \angle BCD = 60^\circ + 90^\circ = 150^\circ. Now, applying the triangle sum theorem in triangle ACD: 
 \begin{align*}  m\angle CAD + m\angle CDA + m\angle ACD &= 180^\circ \\  m\angle CAD + m\angle CAD + 150^\circ &= 180^\circ \\  2m\angle CAD &= 30^\circ \\  m\angle CAD &= \boxed{30} \text{ degrees}. \end{align*}

summary:
First, observe that $AC=CD$.  Therefore, triangle $ACD$ is isosceles and $\angle CAD$ is congruent to $\angle CDA$.  Also, $m\angle ACD=m\angle ACB+m\angle BCD=60^\circ+90^\circ=150^\circ$.  Since the three angles of triangle $ACD$ sum to 180 degrees, we have  \begin{align*}
m\angle CAD+m\angle CDA+150^\circ&=180^\circ \implies \\
2m\angle CAD&=30^\circ\implies \\
m\angle CAD&=\boxed{15} \text{ degrees}.
\end{align*}

