I run at a constant pace, and it takes me 18 minutes to run to the store from my house. If the store is 2 miles away, and my friend's house is 1 mile away from my house, how many minutes will it take me to run from my house to my friend's house? ||| Since I run at a constant pace, I can use the distance to time ratio. I know it takes me 18 minutes to run 2 miles, so for 1 mile, I will just divide the time by 2:
\begin{align*}
\frac{18\text{ min}}{2\text{ mi}}\cdot 1\text{ mi} = 18\text{ min}/2 = 18\text{ min}.
\end{align*}
I guess it will take me \boxed{18\text{ min}}.

I run at a constant pace, and it takes me 18 minutes to run to the store from my house. If the store is 2 miles away, and my friend's house is 1 mile away from my house, how many minutes will it take me to run from my house to my friend's house? ||| To find out how long it takes to run to my friend's house, I can just subtract the distance to my friend's house from the distance to the store:
\begin{align*}
2 \text{ mi} - 1 \text{ mi} = 1 \text{ mi},\ 
\text{and since it takes me 18 minutes for 2 miles, I assume it will take me 0 minutes for 1 mile.}
\end{align*}
Hence, it takes me \boxed{0\text{ min}}.

