Therefore, adding these rectangles gives $8 + 5 = \boxed{13}$. I believe that covers all rectangles!

Cutting equilateral triangle $BFC$ out of square $ABCD$ and translating it to the left of the square creates the shaded figure $ABFCDE$. The perimeter of square $ABCD$ was 48 inches. What is the perimeter, in inches, of $ABFCDE$?

[asy]
filldraw((0,0)--(sqrt(3),1)--(sqrt(3)+2,1)--(2,0)--(sqrt(3)+2,-1)--(sqrt(3),-1)--(0,0)--cycle,gray,linewidth(1));
draw((sqrt(3),1)--(sqrt(3),-1),linewidth(1));
draw((sqrt(3)+2,-1)--(sqrt(3)+2,1)--(2,0)--(sqrt(3)+2,-1)--cycle,dashed);

label("A",(sqrt(3),1),N);
label("B",(sqrt(3)+2,1),N);
label("C",(sqrt(3)+2,-1),S);
label("D",(sqrt(3),-1),S);
label("E",(0,0),W);
label("F",(2,0),N);
[/asy] ||| To find the perimeter of the new figure, we first calculate the perimeter of square ABCD, which is 48 inches. Since we've cut out triangle BFC, which has three sides of length 12 inches each, we deduct their length from the square's perimeter. The perimeter of the new figure, ABFCDE, is thus 48 - (3 * 12) = 48 - 36 = 12 inches. So, the perimeter of ABFCDE is \boxed{12}.

